-- Australian, N.Z. Stocks: Santos, Newcrest, Elders, James Hardie, Woodside
-- Sarah McDonald
-- 2010-06-23T00:36:16Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/australian-n-z-stocks-santos-newcrest-elders-james-hardie-woodside.html

          
          
             Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index  fell
0.9 percent to 4,515.60 as of 10:25 a.m. in Sydney. New
Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  dropped 0.3 percent to 3,044.75 in
Wellington.  
 The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil dropped for the first time in
three days as sales of existing U.S. homes unexpectedly fell in
May, signaling the economy is struggling to recover. Crude oil
for July delivery fell 0.8 percent to settle at $77.21 a barrel
on the New York Mercantile Exchange.  
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) declined 1.8 percent to A$12.95.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU) dropped 1.3 percent to
A$44.70. Australia’s second-largest oil and gas producer said
its Pluto LNG project remains within market guidance, with a
target start-up by the end of February 2011 and first LNG by the
end of March 2011.  
 “However, continued industrial action would delay
mechanical construction activities and consequently impact the
project’s schedule and cost,” the company said.  
 Gold producers: Gold rose on speculation that the dollar
will ease, boosting demand for the precious metal as an
alternative investment. Gold futures for delivery in August rose
10 cents to $1,240.80 on the Comex in New York.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, rose 1.1 percent to A$35.48. Lihir Gold Ltd. (LGL AU)
increased 1.2 percent to A$4.36.  
 Elders Ltd.  (ELD AU) tumbled 8 percent to 40.5 Australian
cents. The world’s largest wool broker was cut to “hold” from
“buy” at Deutsche Bank AG by equity analyst  Philip Pepe .  
 James Hardie Industries  (JHX AU) sank 2.3 percent to A$6.50.
UBS AG analyst  David Leitch  cut the share-price forecast of the
biggest seller of home siding in the U.S. to A$7.72 from A$8.30,
while maintaining a “buy” rating on the stock.  
 Stockland  (SGP AU) dropped 1 percent to A$4.01. Australia’s
biggest housing developer was cut to “sell” from “buy” by
UBS AG analyst  John Freedman .  
